'''Lacus Temporis''' ([[Latin language|Latin]] for ''Lake of Time'') is a small [[lunar mare]] that is located in the northeastern quadrant of the [[Moon]]'s near side. The [[selenographic coordinate]]s of this feature are {{Coord|45.9|N|58.4|E|globe:Moon}}, and it lies within a diameter of 117&nbsp;km.

This small mare is composed of two large, roughly circular patches of relatively smooth surface, with a pair of small, cup-shaped craters located prominently at their intersection. Both of these regions of [[basalt]]ic [[lava]] covered surface have some smaller side lobes, which are most likely impact features that have become flooded. 

Just to the southwest of this feature is the crater [[Chevallier (crater)|Chevallier]] and to the southeast lies [[Carrington (crater)|Carrington]].

