{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
{{details|Physiologus}}
Originally, '''''Physiologist''''' was an ancient collection of stories about [[nature]], which probably appeared in [[Alexandria]] in 200 - 300 [[Anno Domini|A.D.]] The ancient [[Russia]]n ''Physiologist'' ({{Lang-ru|Физиолог}}) in its 15th-century version is a translation from [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]. The Bulgarian version, in turn, was translated from [[Greek language|Greek]] in the 11th - 12th century. ''Physiologist'' contains information on animals and birds (lion, eagle etc.), [[mythical creature]]s ([[phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]], [[centaur]], [[Siren (mythology)|siren]] etc.), stones, and trees. The stories are accompanied by commentaries in the spirit of [[medieval]] [[Christian symbolism]]. The images from the ''Physiologist'' found reflection in the old [[Russian literature]], [[iconography]], and book ornamentation.

